I see the problem. Look closely at your ConfigMap — there are **two** `context-path` lines, and they conflict:

```
server.servlet.context-path=/epaylite-bridge-txt-service     ← still here (txt)
# spring.application.name=epaylite-bridge-txt-service
server.servlet.context-path=/epaylite-bridge-txn-service     ← your new line (txn)
spring.application.name=epaylite-bridge-txn-service
```

You **added** the `txn` line but didn't **remove** the old `txt` line. Now both exist in the same `application.properties`. With duplicate keys in a properties file, Spring keeps the **first** one it reads — which is `txt`. That's why the in-pod test still serves `txt` (404 on `txn`, 200... well, 404 on txt too now because of the duplicate-key confusion, but the point is the old line is still winning/interfering).

So the restart worked fine, the pods are new, the ConfigMap just still contains the stale `txt` line.

## Fix: delete the old `txt` line, keep only `txn`

In `templates/configmap.yaml`, you should have exactly **one** active context-path line. Remove the active `txt` one. The result should look like:

```
#server.servlet.context-path=/epaylite-bridge-txt-service   ← commented, fine to leave
server.servlet.context-path=/epaylite-bridge-txn-service    ← the only ACTIVE one
spring.application.name=epaylite-bridge-txn-service
```

There must be **no uncommented line** that says `txt`.

Let me fix it in the chart for you.Interesting — the chart **I** edited is correct (only one active `txn` line). But the ConfigMap **running in your cluster** still has the active `txt` line plus your added `txn` line. That means the cluster ConfigMap was edited separately/by hand and doesn't match this chart, OR a different chart was applied.

The cluster currently has this (from your `oc get configmap` output), reformatted:

```
#server.servlet.context-path=/epaylite-bridge-txt-service     ← commented (ok)
server.servlet.context-path=/epaylite-bridge-txt-service      ← ACTIVE txt — THIS is the problem
# spring.application.name=epaylite-bridge-txt-service          ← commented (ok)
server.servlet.context-path=/epaylite-bridge-txn-service      ← ACTIVE txn (your addition)
spring.application.name=epaylite-bridge-txn-service
```

Two active `context-path` lines. Spring takes the first → `txt` wins.

## You have two clean ways forward

**Option 1 — deploy the corrected chart (recommended, since the chart is already right):**

```
helm upgrade epaybridgetxn ./dev/charts/epaylite-bridge-txn-service -n dev-bridge
oc rollout restart deploy/epaybridgetxn-epaylitebridgetxn -n dev-bridge
oc rollout status  deploy/epaybridgetxn-epaylitebridgetxn -n dev-bridge
```
This overwrites the messy cluster ConfigMap with the clean one (single `txn` line).

**Option 2 — edit the ConfigMap directly in the cluster** (if you can't run helm right now):
```
oc edit configmap epaybridgetxn-config -n dev-bridge
```
Find the active (uncommented) line `server.servlet.context-path=/epaylite-bridge-txt-service` and delete it. Leave only the `txn` one. Save, then restart:
```
oc rollout restart deploy/epaybridgetxn-epaylitebridgetxn -n dev-bridge
```

Option 1 is better — it keeps cluster and chart in sync. With Option 2 the cluster works but your chart and cluster could drift again on the next deploy.

## After the restart, verify

```
